In .NET 10 we had the sync-over-async opt-in configured. What breaks in .NET 11?

data.content:
**In .NET 11, sync I/O on the Cosmos DB provider is fully removed — no opt-in exists anymore.** Every synchronous call (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`) will **always throw** at runtime, regardless of configuration.

Your `.NET 10` opt-in (`EnableSyncIO` or equivalent) is silently ignored.

**Fix — convert to async:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Every method becomes `async Task<T>` (or `async Task`)
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods, which will ripple up the call chain (controllers, services, etc.)

This is not optional — there is no workaround or compatibility switch in EF Core 11. See [dotnet/efcore#37059](https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/37059) for the tracking issue.
